text:
Dey Street, east from West Street, showing prominently the north side of this thoroughfare. The frontage seen extends from West to Washington Street's. Towering above is the Woolworth Bldg. on Broadway. To the right is one of the Hudson Terminal Bldgs. View 2 is later and shows the gasoline station at the corner and a demolition adjoining. Two new outstanding structures appear in the background. These are the new Downtown Post Office and the Transportation Bldg. The latter is to the right and flanks the Woolworth Bldg.

1: September 1914
2: April 28, 1940

George L. Balgue, photo

P. L. Sperr

Code II A-2c
April 8, 1936

Dey Street, north side, east from West Street, showing prominently, in the background, the two 22-story Hudson and Manhattan Railroad Terminal Buildings on the west side of Church Street. The one seen on the right is known as the Cortlandt Building extending from Cortlandt to Dey Streets, and the other is the Fulton Building, extending from Dey to Fulton Streets. A foot-bridge connects the two buildings. Also shown (right foreground) are Nos. 122 and 121 West Street, at, and adjoining the S.E. corner of Dey Street.

April 17, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

West Street, east side, from Dey (right) to Fulton (left) Streets. In the background are the towering structures identified with lower Broadway at Wall Street. Co-mingled in the center are the Equitable, Bankers Trust, Bank of Manhattan, City Bank-Farmers Trust and The Equitable Trust buildings. To the right appears the Irving Trust Company and Trinity Church. A portion of the Washington Market is in the lower left corner.

1939

Alexander Alland

This phot is one of a series that appeared in the published volume "Portrait of N. Y." by Felix Reisenberg and Alex. Alland, IRGV.

West Street, east side, south from Dey Street (Telegram Square). Shown under demolition are several buildings at the S. E. corner. In the background are the lofty office structures comprising the business&financial district. Generally speaking the massive structures are the former and the delicate pinnacles, the latter.
